data.content:
**MSTest Collection Assertions**

Your test works but produces unhelpful failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest has better options:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure shows *both* values instead of just "false"
- **Add messages** to `Assert.IsTrue` so failures are diagnosable
- **`Assert.AreEqual` replaces `Assert.IsTrue(x == y)`** — always prefer specific assertions
- Use **`Any()`** instead of `Single()` + null check when you just need existence

**Other useful collection assertions in MSTest:**

```csharp
// Check a specific item exists
Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));

// CollectionAssert for deeper checks
CollectionAssert.AllAreSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList); // same items, any order
```

The general rule: **avoid bare `Assert.IsTrue`** — use the most specific assertion available so failures tell you *what* went wrong.
